# Pane Scheduling

Chartered 2026-07-14 from Joel: "with the observer we can easily
schedule panes to AWAKEN LATER or get REVIVED." Every primitive already
exists — inngest runs durable scheduled jobs, the dispatcher wakes
targets through herdr, continuation prompts carry full resume context.
This effort composes them.

## Finish line

One durable schedule with three verbs, each proven live once, on time,
with receipts: **WAKE** (a prompt lands in an existing pane/agent at
time T), **SPAWN** (a new pane at time T runs a task brief), **REVIVE**
(a new pane at time T boots from an open loop's continuation prompt and
resumes the dead thread). Both Joel and agents can schedule (`joelclaw
wake …` / an observer-family tool). Durability rides inngest — entries
survive restarts because `step.sleepUntil` does. Fired panes appear in
the **observer family herdr session** (Joel, charter), labeled ⏰.
Pending schedules are visible somewhere Joel actually looks. Misfires
(machine asleep at T) fire on recovery flagged **late**, never silently
dropped.

## Vocabulary

- **WAKE / SPAWN / REVIVE** — the three verbs: prompt an existing pane;
  new pane + task brief; new pane + a loop's continuation prompt.
- **due signal** — the gateway event the inngest function emits when a
  schedule fires; the dispatcher executes the verb.
- **late fire** — a due signal delivered after its time T (sleep,
  outage); executed anyway, labeled late in the receipt.

## Notes

- **The clock is inngest** (Joel, charter, 2026-07-14: "inngest has
  scheduled jobs") — no new daemons, no cron files; durability and
  event-driven revival come free. The dispatcher executes; it already
  owns herdr wake machinery and the family registry.
- Spawned/revived panes live in the observer family session (Joel,
  charter) — automation stays with automation; labels make it scannable.
- Skills: `herdr-orchestration`; repo law for inngest functions
  (joelclaw `.claude/CLAUDE.md` validation checklist).
- Gates stay sacred: revived/spawned panes are ordinary pi sessions —
  never gated observer/dispatcher roles.
- **Execution authorized** for `kind: task` questions (Joel, 2026-07-14,
  charter): workers build, steering reviews/commits/installs.

## Decision ledger

<!-- one line per closed question: gist + link -->

- **SPAWN proven live end to end (2026-07-15)**: `joelclaw wake in 2m` → inngest sleepUntil → due signal (late: false, fired 1s after target) → dispatcher fate → fresh-tab fallback → pi booted the brief → "SCHEDULED PANE ALIVE: 05:28:18 UTC". Two deployment lessons on the record: new inngest functions need a bus restart (worker-supervisor child kill), and tab-create returns root_pane where split returns pane (parse fixed, tested). WAKE and REVIVE still await their live proof.

- [Teach the Fleet to Schedule](./teach-the-fleet-to-schedule.svx) — skill + graft staged, installed on flagg, pushed fleet-wide; first cold proof FABRICATED a receipt under tool denial → receipt rule added to skill and block; second cold proof (tools allowed) produced a real registry-verified schedule with a well-designed brief. Blaine/panda get it on next sync.

- [Build Dispatcher Verb Execution](./build-dispatcher-verb-execution.svx) — due signals are a first-class fate: WAKE/SPAWN/REVIVE planned pure, executed via herdr in the family session, idempotent per scheduleId, refusal receipts, too-small fallback; 75 tests; live end-to-end = steering acceptance (running).

- [Build the Schedule (bus side)](./build-schedule-events-function-cli.svx) — `pane/schedule.requested` contract + inngest `step.sleepUntil` function w/ cancellation race + Redis pending registry + `joelclaw wake at|in|list|cancel`; live receipt: real schedule enqueued (200) and cleanly cancelled. Dispatcher execution now READY.

## Not yet specified

- Recurring schedules (every weekday at 9am) — one-shots first; recurrence
  graduates when a real need shows up.
- Whether REVIVE should also work from an observation page (not just a
  loop) — the reflector's citations would make that possible.
- Cancellation UX beyond `joelclaw wake cancel <id>` (paper button?).

## Out of scope

- Replacing the observer tick or the nightly LaunchAgents with inngest —
  they work; this effort adds a scheduler, it doesn't migrate cadences.
- Waking Joel (notifications are the dispatcher's existing lane).
